defaultQ3default              defaultHow Should Expenditure On Improvdefaulting Safety At Level Crossings Be Prioritised in Relation To Other Demands On The Rail Budget?default&#xa0;
defaultA3
default              
defaultThis is largely a question for other respondents.    But in general terms the fact that Level Crossings represent such a major risk to the safety of the railw
defaultay is likely to be a major factor in determining priorities.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe policing of Level Crossings represents a sig
defaultnificant and growing commitment 
defaultfor BTP.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ4default              default              defaultIs Network Rail Giving Sufficient Priority to Improving Safety At Level Crossings?default&#xa0;defaultA4
default              
defaultIn recent 
defaultyears Network Rail’s commitment to this subject has been unquestionable.  The company has pursued the improvement of safety in this context with passion and dedication.  This comment is made from the point of view of a close partner with visibility only of
default central efforts around a few work streams.   There is nothing to suggest that this energy is not operating throughout the whole Level Crossings project.  Network Rail has appointed the parent of a victim of an accident at a Level Crossing as their Level C
defaultrossings ‘Champion’.  This was a brave move and a bold statement of commitment.  Nobody who has listened to her lecture on the subject of Level Crossing safety can be left in any doubt that there is still much to be done or that this work is of the greates
defaultt importance.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ5default              defaultIs Government Policy and Regulatory Action By The Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in Relation to Safety at Level Crossings Adequate?  What More Should The Government and ORR Do?default&#xa0;
defaultA5
default              
defaultBTP is not in a position to assist with this question. 
default The Force works closely with ORR, particularly in the aftermath of incidents.  In this context the working relationship between ORR and BTP is good and highly valued.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ6default              defaultHow Should Legislation Governing Level Crossings Be Updated?default&#xa0;defaultA6
default              
defaultBTP awaits the pub
defaultlication of the Law Commission’s
default defaultreport on Level Crossings.  We submit that the Law Commission’s comments in Part One of their consultation paper on this subject (2010) provides a good summary of the current legal position,
default (9)
default viz:
default&#xa0;
default              
default“
defaultThe legislation gove
defaultrning level crossings is complex and antiquated, much of it dating back to the nineteenth century when the main railways were constructed. The provisions relevant to level crossings are difficult to access. This arises partly because they are spread across
default legislation relating to a number of different subject areas – railways, highways/roads, health and safety, planning and criminal law. Furthermore, the provisions are contained in a combination of public general Acts, private Acts, bye-laws, and subordinat
defaulte legislation in the form of Orders and Regulations, many of which have been amended heavily in recent years.
default3 
defaultSome of the Acts have been partially repealed and some of their provisions have become spent or obsolete, causing confusion as to which 
defaultprovisions still apply and which are redundant. Many of the Acts of the Victorian era contain terminology that is no longer in use such as “turnpike roads” and “statute labour roads”. Such terminology is unhelpful when trying to interpret the law in a mode
defaultrn context. There has been no attempt at consolidating the legislation in this area.” (P1 Para 1.2)
default&#xa0;
defaultOne particular legislative anomaly is currently cau
defaultsing considerable difficulty in 
defaultrespect of enforcement of Road Traffic Act provisions at Level Crossings
default.  Recent work revealed that the Chief Constable of British Transport Police probably does not have powers under s172 Road Traffic Act 1988 to require the registered keeper of a motor vehicle to supply the details of the driver of the vehicle at the time o
defaultf a suspected offence.  The problem is a technical one that arises from the construction of this section.  The Department for Transport (DfT) are aware of the problem and are working on a solution.  In the meantime the co-operation of geographic police for
defaultces is being employed via the good offices of the Association of Chief Police Officers (ACPO).  What is disheartening is that this lacuna was first identified over thirty years ago and was corrected by the British Railways Act 1986.  However the principal 
defaultlegislation at the time, the Road Traffic Act 1972, was replaced shortly afterwards by the Road Traffic Act 1988 and it appears that the changes brought about by the 1986 Act have been lost.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultThe legislation on railway trespass is also unclear.  The princ
defaultipal piece of legislation creating an offence of criminal trespass on railways is s55 British Transport Commission Act 1949.  This provision largely recreates the offences that previously existed in the Acts of Parliament that governed the individual railw
defaultay companies.  What is uncertain is whether or not it is possible for the offence to be committed on a level crossing when it is ‘closed’ for the passage of a train.  This issue is acute at crossings without physical barriers.  Pedestrians passing in front
default of trains at crossings are a serious problem.  S55 requires that a  trespass warning notice is displayed at the nearest passenger station – not at Level Crossings.  The relevance of this requirement is hard to see and is itself an anachronism.   The Law C
defaultommission consultation discusses this offence at useful length (Part 13 2010).  It notes: that  “ A particular feature of the section 55 offence is its obscurity”  (
default10
default)  We therefore agree that this area of law should be subject to review with the intentio
defaultn of making the offence clear, both generally and specifically in relation to Level Crossings.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultThe rai
defaultlway industry and occasionally 
defaultthe Force are called to deal with gates that have been left open at User Worked Crossings.  The law covering this problem
default is to be found in the Railway Clauses Consolidation Act 1845 and in the Railway Clauses Consolidation (Scotland) Act 1845.  These Acts create a penalty for failing to close a gate.  To enforce this the individual who fails to close the gate has to be iden
defaulttified.  We would suggest that consideration is given to the creation of a duty on the landowner to ensure that gates are shut. 
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultA case could be made for Level Crossing offences to attract higher penalties than those for equivalent offences on other road
defaults (failure to comply with a road traffic signal for example).   
defaultThis would require a detailed assessment of the potential for a deterrent effect if such a change were not seen to be punitive.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQ7default              default       How Should Public Awareness of Safety at Level Crossings Be Improved?default&#xa0;defaultA7
default              
defaultThis is an area that would benefit from continued specialised research.  There could be possible opportunities to increase the amount time given to Level Crossings in initial 
defaultdriver training and testing, both for new drivers and for specialist driving qualifications (Good Vehicles etc).
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is a fundamental problem that road vehicle drivers will take risks at Level        Crossings when they would hesitate to do so at other 
defaultpoints of traffic control.  The ‘human factors’ aspects of this behaviour may benefit from further research.
